        "Line charts are used to represent the relation between two data X and Y on the respective axis. Let’s see a few samples"

      "source": [
        "# Sample #1\n",
        "# importing the required libraries\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",

        "x = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4])\n",

        "### II.Histogram\n",
        "The histogram is the graphical representation of a set of numerical data distribution across. It is a kind of bar plot with X-axis and Y-axis represents the bin ranges and frequency respectively. How to read or represent this chart.\n",
        "\n",
        "Let say the example, set of students marks in the ranges and frequency as below. Here we could understand the range and frequency cut off exactly."

      },
      "source": [
        "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "fig,ax = plt.subplots(1,1)\n",

        "a = np.array([25,42,48,55,60,62,67,70,30,38,44,50,54,58,75,78,85,88,89,28,35,90,95])\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.hist(a, bins = [20,40,60,80,100])\n",

        "ax.set_title(\"Student's Score\")\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.set_xticks([0,20,40,60,80,100])\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('Marks Scored')\n",

        "### III.Pie Chart\n",

Each of the slices of pie is called a wedge with values of different sizes.\n",

        "This chart is widely used to represent the composition collection. Perfect for the categorical data type."

      "source": [
        "### VII. Heatmap\n",
        "A heatmap is one of my favorite visualization techniques among the other charts. basically, a set of variable correlations is represented by various shades of the same color. Usually, the darker shades of the chart represent the higher correlations values than the lighter shade. this map would help Data Scientists to figure out how to target variable is correlated with other dependent variables in the given data set. Less correlated variables can be removed for further analysis, we could say this helps us during the feature selection process. Later grouping them under X, Y as our target and followed by test and train split."
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "### VIII. Boxplot\n",
        "A Boxplot is a type of chart often used in the Data Science life cycle, especially during Explanatory Data Analysis (EDA). Which represents the distribution of data in the form of quartiles or percentiles. Q1 represents the first quartile (25th percentile), Q2 is the second quartile (50th percentile/median), Q3 represents the third quartile (Q3) and Q4 represents the fourth quartile or the largest value.\n",
        "\n",
        "Using this plot we could identify the outliers very quickly and easily. This is a very effective plot all among the plots. So after the removal of outliers, the data set needs to undergo some sort of statistical test and fine-tune for further analysis."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 374
